  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "My Website is down since 2 Days. What should I do?",
  "response": "If your website has been down for two days, here are some steps you can take to diagnose and resolve the issue:\n\n1. **Check for Outages**: \n   - Use a website like Down For Everyone Or Just Me (downforeveryoneorjustme.com) to see if your site is down for others or just you.\n   - Check your hosting provider's website or social media channels for any reported outages.\n\n2. **Contact Your Hosting Provider**: \n   - Reach out to your hosting provider\u2019s support team. They can provide information about server status, maintenance, or any issues affecting your site.\n\n3. **Review Your Domain Status**:\n   - Ensure your domain name hasn\u2019t expired. You can check this with a WHOIS lookup service.\n   - If your domain is expired, you\u2019ll need to renew it through your domain registrar.\n\n4. **Check DNS Settings**:\n   - Review your DNS settings to ensure they are correctly configured. You can use tools like DNS Checker to verify if your DNS records are propagating properly.\n\n5. **Check for Website Errors**:\n   - If you have access to your website files or backend, check for any error messages in the logs (e.g., error logs, access logs) that could provide insight into the issue.\n   - Look for common issues, such as server overload, misconfigured settings, or issues with recently installed plugins or themes.\n\n6. **Restore from Backup**:\n   - If you have backups of your website, consider restoring it to a previous working state while you investigate the issue.\n\n7. **Check for Malware or Hacking**:\n   - Run a security scan on your website to check for malware or signs of hacking. Some hosting providers offer this service, or you can use third-party tools.\n\n8. **Review Recent Changes**:\n   - If you or someone else made recent changes to the website (like updates, new plugins, or server changes), consider rolling back those changes to see if that resolves the issue.\n\n9. **Monitor Uptime**:\n   - Once your website is back up, consider using uptime monitoring services to alert you of any future downtime.\n\n10. **Consider Professional Help**:\n    - If you are unable to resolve the issue yourself, consider hiring a web developer or IT professional with experience in troubleshooting website issues.\n\nTaking these steps should help you identify and resolve the issue with your website.",
